node.text: On the coast of Portugal, Gordon Ramsay visits one of the most unique vineyards on the planet where the vines grow in the sand. A new season of Gordon Ramsay: Uncharted airs Monday, May 31 at 9/8c.

node.title: Gordon Ramsay: Uncharted – A Vineyard in the Sand

node.accessibility_caption: Photo by National Geographic Travel on September 14, 2021. May be an image of nature and arctic.

node.text: Photo by @kiliiiyuyan / Hoarfrost coats sea ice at the edge where it meets the Arctic Ocean in Alaska. This kind of ice forms when humid air settles on the sea ice and immediately freezes, creating ice crystals in beautiful formations. It’s a bad sign in the early spring, when temperatures should be far below freezing around-the-clock. #ice #arctic #alaska

node.accessibility_caption: Photo by National Geographic Travel on September 14, 2021. May be an image of nature and text.

node.text:
Photos by @babaktafreshi / With the Earth's rotation, stars appear to rain down on the erupting Volcán de Fuego ("fire volcano"). The long-exposure image is a result of a time-lapse sequence. During this November 2019 night in Guatemala, I recorded an average of 10 explosions an hour with incandescent ejecta rising several hundred meters above the summit. 
Located only 11 miles (18 kilometers) from the World Heritage city of Antigua, the volcano has been continuously active since the catastrophic eruption on June 3, 2018. That eruption affected almost two million people and hundreds of people died in the nearby villages. Many are still missing. ⁣⁣According to the U.S. Geological Survey, on that day instead of slow-moving lava, Fuego erupted with a mix of ash, rock, and volcanic gases—a rapid pyroclastic flow that surprised the villagers who were used to frequent minor eruptions. The flows raced down at speeds as high as 450 miles (724 kilometers) an hour and engulfed whole villages at the bottom. A similar event was responsible for wiping out Pompeii in Italy about 2,000 years ago. ⁣
Explore the world at night with me @babaktafreshi. #twanight #volcano #guatemala #longexposure

node.text: Photo by @daisygilardini / Antarctica's gray skies are perfect for iceberg photography. Overcast days allow photographers to avoid excessive contrast and get better overall exposure, translating to more details and deeper shades of blue. Follow me @daisygilardini for more images and behind-the-scenes stories

node.accessibility_caption: Photo by National Geographic Travel on September 13, 2021. May be an image of nature, cloud and twilight.

node.text: Photo by @krystlejwright / I am always excited when I see clouds in the morning. If the sun hits the horizon just right, it can light the sky up with an array of intense and spectacular colors. Knowing how popular this spot can get, I arrived at Hamersley Gorge in Karijini National Park at first light to beat the crowds—and it was certainly worth the effort.

node.text: Video by Keith Ladzinski @ladzinski / These are the structural remains of an old monastery high above the valley floor along the Tibetan Plateau. I filmed this little clip here on the way to Mount Everest Base Camp. The road passes through valley after valley full of rich history and old ruins such as these.

node.accessibility_caption: Photo by National Geographic Travel on September 13, 2021. May be an image of 1 person, dog and outdoors.

node.text:
Photo by @estherhorvath / Trude Hohle, a citizen of Longyearbyen, Svalbard, holds a puppy at a private dog yard outside the city. Because of wildlife protection, there are many rules in Svalbard. Dogs are not allowed to run free. They must stay in a dog yard outside of town and be on their leash when walking. Many locals have their own dogs that they use for dog sledding, and the dogs are wonderful company during the dark months of the polar night. Trude left her business life in Oslo behind and moved to Longyearbyen, following her dreams to work and live in one of the northernmost Arctic places on Earth. She spends much of her free time training and handling polar dogs.
Please follow @estherhorvath for more polar stories.

node.text: Photo by @dina_litovsky / I love walking around New York City at night and catching fleeting moments happening inside the metropolis. This image was taken in the East Village. For more photos, follow me @dina_litovsky.

node.text:
Photo by @stephen_matera / Larch trees in autumn color the Alpine Lakes Wilderness in the central Cascades, Washington. The larch is a deciduous conifer that grows in the mountains of the western United States and Canada. Its surprisingly soft needles turn golden yellow and fall off in autumn. I love these trees because they glow when backlit by the sun. 
Follow me @stephen_matera for more images like this from Washington and around the world. #larch #DeciduousConifer #autumn
